This tool provides a quick way to level your HyperCube bed. I know, auto bed leveling will take care of everything except that I don't like it. Auto bed leveling moves the Z axis up and down as it moves across the bed which I think is bad. I would rather have a perfectly level bed and not use auto bed leveling. This tool provides an easy way to get a perfectly level bed.

This tool is my remix of a great design I found on Thingiverse. I made modifications to accommodate the HyperCube bearing rod spacing which is 41.5 mm. The dial indicator does a far more precise job of leveling the bed than using the drag paper method. I have found that my first layer is much more consistent. It is especially helpful for larger prints. It is also quicker to check the four corners with the dial indicator than using paper because I don't have to bring x axis near the bed. I can just zero the dial indicator on one corner and adjust the other three corners to match.

My procedure:
Attach the dial indicator to left side of X axis and move the carriage backward so that indicator is in rear corner. Zero the indicator.
Move the carriage forward and take reading on the front left corner. Adjust the bed leveling screw until the dial indicator reads zero.
Move dial indicator to right side of X axis carriage being careful not to zero it. Take a reading on front right side of bed and adjust the bed leveling screw until the indicator reads zero.
Move the carriage backwards and take reading on the rear right corner. Adjust the bed leveling screw until the dial indicator reads zero.
Move the extruder to the middle of the bed and do you normal Z height adjustment. All four corners are level so no check should be needed other than the middle of the bed

This is the Dial Indicator I used although you can buy a similar unit from Harbor Freight.
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01G9K8U5G. Cost is $28.

Assembly requires a 6 mm x 35 mm Philips head screw and 6 mm nut for the dial indicator mounting. You'll need a 3 mm x 15 mm cap head screw and a 3 mm Nylock nut for the lever. This is the Dial Indicator I used although you can buy a similar unit from Harbor Freight.

title: Clip holder for Anker Micro USB to USB C adapter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a holder / clip for attaching tiny micro USB to USB C adapters to USB cables. I use some micro USB cables for charging and data connections to both micro USB and USB C devices and, with the adapter being so tiny, I needed a way of attaching the adapter to the USB cable when it's not in use. I created this model for the adapters made by Anker, but It may fit similar adapters - please let me know if it does.

This holder is designed for a TIGHT fit. (I want this holder/clip to NOT get lost.) You may need to trim any excess plastic from the inside of the holder for it to fit onto the adapter. For the adapters I have, it is easier to slide the holder onto the adapter from the USB C end. It becomes a VERY tight fit near the micro USB end. As well, you may have to flex the cable clip a bit before it will easily snap onto a USB cable. I use needle nose pliers to gently flex each side a tiny amount when a holder is newly printed.

I've included a simple tool to help remove the holder and protect the USB C end of the adapter. To use the tool, put the USB C end of the adapter into the slot in the tool and push the adapter downwards. Easy. :-) The tool is designed to ensure that the pressure is placed on the plastic part of the adapter and not on the metal (and fragile) USB C end.

Printer:

HICTOP 3DP-17

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

Rectilinear, minimal infill length 0

Notes:

Tested with:
PLA
0.2mm layer height
1 outline/perimeter shell
20% infill
0 minimal infill length

Using more than one shell caused my prints to be too wide.
I set the slicer to 0 minimal infill length because the parts are small and thin and need to be filled.

Intro

How I designed this is simple, but it took a few iterations. It was difficult to get the exact fit I was looking for, especially with the rounded corners on the adapter. The only really important lesson from this is to try to make shapes that can be quickly printed out to test their fit. It saves time and plastic!

Part 1: The Holder

I used Adobe Illustrator to draw two rounded rectangles representing the outline of the holder, and I used the exact measurements features of line drawing to make sure the dimensions were what I wanted. This shape was then exported from Illustrator as an SVG file. The free Inkscape vector drawing program would have worked just as well, and (in hindsight) using the sketch tool in Autodesk's 123D Design would probably have been even faster.

The simple holder outline exported from Adobe Illustrator

Autodesk's free 123D Design was used next to import the SVG file as a sketch and to extrude it into 3D. I only extruded it to 1mm for the first few attempts so I could get very fast 3D prints to test the fit with. Those rounded corners were frustrating... I initially used the "3D Print -> Desktop 3D Printer" to automatically export the object into MeshMixer, but I later started to use "Export as 3D -> STL" to create the STL file to print.

With the quickly printed prototype, I used a flashlight to shine light between the holder prototype and the adapter to see how the fit was looking. I then tweaked the shape in Illustrator and repeated the process until I was satisfied with it. I think it took about 6 attempts.

Once the holder fit seemed to be correct, I extruded it to the full length, printed it, and tried it out. It fit!

Part 2: The Clip

With the holder working I needed a clip to attach it to a USB cable. This part was quite simple. I used Adobe Illustrator to create a simple 270 degree arc with rounded ends, a center radius to match a typical USB cable, and a stroke width I thought would work.

However, unlike the two shapes used for the holder, this shape was still just a line in Illustrator and wouldn't export properly. To fix it I used the "Object -> Path -> Outline Stroke" command to create a path outlining this shape. That outline was what was exported as an SVG.

The simple clip outline from Adobe Illustrator

Autodesk's free 123D Design was again used to import this new SVG file as a sketch and to extrude it to the length of the holder. The two objects were then lined up, and the clip part was sunk somewhat into the holder. That depth was a guess as to what would be strong yet flexible, and I think it ended up on the strong side as the clip needs to be manually worked a bit after printing to be loose enough to easily clip onto USB cables. :-) But the goal was to not lose the adapters, so this was fine by me.

The two objects were then made into one using the Combine -> Merge function.

Part 3: A Removal Tool

Since I'd tried to make this holder fit tightly, there came the problem of removing it without damaging the adapter. The holder fits tightest at the micro USB end of the adapter, so pushing it off the USB C end was the way to go. However, that could easily bend and damage the USB C end, so it seemed like a simple tool was in order.

Making the tool was almost exactly the same as making the holder part itself. I made two rounded rectangles in Adobe Illustrator, the inner one sized to be slightly larger than the USB C connector, and the other sized to be slightly smaller than the inner size of the holder. This image was exported as an SVG file, imported into 123D Design. I extruded the shape into a tube of that is slightly longer than the length of the USB C connector to ensure that any downward pressure would end up on the outside plastic of the adapter and not on the metal USB C connector.

The base of the tool is a simple circle extruded out and "snapped" to one end of the extruded tube. The two objects were then made into one using the "Combine -> Merge" function.

For strength, the bottom edge of the tube was rounded using the "Modify -> Fillet" option. Straight 90 degree angles on plastics can snap easily, and using this function gave that joint some support.

Finally, "Export as 3D -> STL" to create the STL file to print.

Done!

So there you go. It was my first "thing", and it was a simple one. In hindsight, I probably could have done it all in 123D Design, but I'm familiar with Illustrator and so it was the natural first choice for doing the outlines to extrude.

I hope that explanation shows just how easy it can be to make your own simple thing. Happy making!

Used an flaser.com 40W hobby laser. For the dominoes I used 1/4" Oak (Home Depot sells them in 6" wide planks). One plank will do the whole domino set - less than $10.
I also did a 1/4" birch plywood fingerbox where to store the dominoes. Home depot sells this material in 2'x4' boards for less than $10. I had to cut both sets of boards into smaller boards with a saw before putting them inside the laser cutter. Both woods cut on my 40W laser at 10% speed, 100% power.
I engrave the details at 100% speed, 20 to 25% power. Did in Corel, but you can also use the Acrobat Reader files.

This is a simple bracket to hold down the Hytera PD6xx-Series charging cradles.

Often the cradle lifts up, when the radio is pulled out of the cradle, because the cradle is to light weight.

comments.text: Thank You very much:) i put some love making it :) no i didnt made one because this is first prototype. It looks great but inside is a mess... when i will have some spare time i will do upgrade. but for now i can tell You that i used 4 standard short (about 10-20 cm long) usb cables. When You cut the plastic on female side it will fit. For now i glue them and check every cable if it is working with simple usb drive mount to pc. Then I use standard 20 or 10 cm hdmi extend cable. The hole is big so You dont need to cut plastic around female ending. I glue it too. DC power cable socket is just standard one with just two holes (with out ground i think). I model it to the one i had from store . and off course glue it. but before that i took standard 2.5 amps selphone charger, and my friend solder two cables for that power slot i mention before. One cable from that two (dont matter wich one) You need to cut in half (between power cable socket and charger). Now i bought standard "foot lamp switch", You dont need all off this, just main switch (for 220volts) and spring. Just google some transparent foot lamp switch and You will see what You will need. You take two cables for this switch and connect it to this power cable in charger i wrote about before. So this will be Your power switch. Now You need assemble all the lights or just the left eye light. There is instruction to download in files section for that. First take 4 eye_switch_stick.stl (yes You need it 4). Glue them to eye_switch_back.stl . If You will have them in hands You will see how - they all fit in corners just like they should. Now hot glue this power switch from lamp switch to eye_switch_back.stl. be sure You have light in left eye placed correct in the hole, and then put this eye in front case from behind. from inside of the case to out side - it will fit only one way, but be sure pupil is inthe place You want. Now You need to put spring on to the power switch from lamp and glue those 4 parts (sticks) to interior of the front case. There are some small holes for that so You will see this. I left the charger case and glue it inside, also glue the fan. Place all the light - You can glue right eye now. Now is the tricky part:) connect all cables (4x usb + hdmi + as small as You get get usb for power + sd card extender cable. My sd card extender should be pleced in back case part now. There is no raspberry special place... this is mainly whay this is still .8 version. There are so meny cables so when You will bend them with sense and patience all will fit and raspberry pi will hold still with out any screw :P Now is the time to squeeze front case with back case... it is not elegant but You see it works for me... i still did not have time to upgrade this model. Hope will be able to do it soon, but You know... life :P for 90% front will fit with back perfectlly so You dont need to glue it. It depends on printer and material You use. If You didnt done it before glue pupils and that is it :P it is late here in Poland and I'm going to sleep now, but can make some photos and graphical instruction tomorrow if You want, just let me know:)  also i will post some reference photose for additional parts like this power switch. Sorry about my poor English and hope i helped You in some way:)

description.text:
This is a simple little box that holds a flyback diode for solenoid flyback protection in my virtual pinball cabinet: http://lilmikey.com/2017/02/16/virtual-pinball-cabinet/

The diode is needed to 'short circuit' any current caused by the shaft springing back through the solenoid coil. The diode allows any current generated to recycle through the solenoid which may reduce reset time of the solenoid but protects the relay or other sensitive electronics from the reverse current.

It's basically a tiny snap together box with holes in the sides for the wires and a mounting screw hole.

Notes:

I printed mine using Simplify3D software and my Dremel Idea Builder, using PLA filament and printing in High detail with 100% infill (solid).

The software will likely try to add support material on the inside where the ink will go. This would be too hard to remove and you can get by without it. Instead, I used manually-added supports on each end, and placing one of the flat sides down on the bed kept it stable enough during printing.

The pen was designed in Fusion 360. First the ink refill was measured and modeled, and then the pen body was modeled around it. Before making the larger model, I created a few "pen tip" test pieces with different hole diameters to find the best size hole for the ink to fit in.

A bluetooth communicator badge for those who need to communicate with their orbiting starship. (or with friends or co-workers via the cellular system)
The idea is that you could carry this in your shirt pocket, and use voice command to quickly call people at the other end of the house, rather than having to pull out your phone or (gasp) get up off the sofa. Its usefulness is really dependent on good voice-command software in the phone that you pair it with, otherwise it would just be more convenient to dial the call directly.
Note that the badge does not have a speaker - you'll have to somehow get your phone to use speakerphone when you take calls using the badge. It does have a microphone for (hopefully) improved call quality on the other end, and an instant voice-dial / answer call button.

IMPORTANT NOTE: I'm abandoning this thing. After further testing, I found that there is no way to initiate a call after a brief badge tap, which is contrary to the design principle. I'll attempt to create a derivative using different electronics and a different printed case design. I HAVE NOT PRINTED THIS ITEM. I'm still working out various aspects of the electronics. But, if anyone wants to know, here are the instructions: The badge is designed to use the electronics from a BlueAction BAE-815 headset. For the most part, you can simply remove the electronics from the BAE and drop them into the badge. You'll have to discard the speaker (there's no room for it, and the volume is too low, anyway), and possibly lengthen the wire for the microphone. However, the push-button on the BAE is terrible, so you'll need to find or make your own and wire it into the one on the BAE. I haven't decided on a way to do this, and since I'm abandoning the design, I'll probably never come up with anything. The other issue with the electronics it that most cellphones will think the badge has a speaker, and try to send call audio to it. I'm still trying to get my android to switch to speakerphone when I place or take calls using the badge. If and when I figure it out, I will post instructions here. title: Konvas Lomo oct 18 to Canon EF mount Adapter

description.text:
This is a adapter for ancient Konvas Camera with Lomo, Lenkinap, KMZ russian lens with oct 18 mount for Canon EOS EF mount.
Konvas - Lomo oct-18 lens have a 57mm focal flange distance and 47mm diameter.
(source: http://konvas.org/faq/faqs/faq/konvas-oct18-ost18-oct19-ost19-lens-mount-diagrams).

With this adapter you can focus at infinity if you can physically fit the lens in yours camera.

If you use on EOS reflex camera Check the back focal distance (BFD) of the lens isn't to long or you risk to damage yours camera. Most Canon reflex have 11mm space between Mount Flange and inside body, any lens with bigger BFD can damage your camera our you cant focus at infinite.

If you use on a mirror less camera with a extra adaptor (Canon M, Sony E, Micro 4/3) you can you use all oct-18 lenses without worries

This version have 3 holes with a insert for M4 nuts to secure the lens with M4 nylon screw, and also a STL model without secure holes you can modify for your need (you can melt in also copper insert nuts).

The design is not industrial standard but is working well.
If you use prime lenses notice you need to focus using the internal barrel, because the external barrel is locked with this system, be careful because the inner barrel can completely come out of the lenses if you try to focus to close.

The STL model is upside down: turn 180° on you slicer to use less support.
The photos as example are shot with a Lomo 135mm t4.0 and 75mm t2.3 lenses on a old APS-C Canon 400D without focus assist

Printer:

Tatara Steel A8

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

66℅

Notes:

The prototype you see in the picture was printed with a Anet A8, slicing with CraftWare.
PLA 1.75 mm
Temperature 210°
Layer height 0.1mm
Draw speed 36mm/sec
Shell loop count 2
Top/Bottom Layer 3
Infill density 66% with Triangle grid
ATTENTION: The STL model is upside down: turn 180° on you slicer to use less support.

Finishing

If your printer is over extruding or not precise enough you need to papper sand out some microns the 47mm inside hole. But better to thight than to lose.
The side with EF mount don't need any finishing but lock and unlock few times on a dummy EF female mount and then blow with some air to avoid dust going inside yours Camera.

If you plan to use your oct-18 lens only with EF mount camera you can force the lens into the adapter.
